<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-equilibrium-stability" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Stability of Equilibrium Solutions</title>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       INTRO PROSE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    Recall from <xref ref="sec-equilibrium-solutions"/> that an <alert>equilibrium solution</alert>
    is a constant solution <m>y(t) = C</m>, found by setting <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = 0</m>.
    In <xref ref="sec-pop-logistic"/> and <xref ref="sec-pop-doomsday"/>, we found
    that both population models had equilibrium solutions at <m>P(t) = 0</m> and
    <m>P(t) = M</m>. But what made those two pages interesting was not the equilibrium
    solutions themselves, it was what happened to all the other solutions nearby.
  </p>

  <p>
    In the logistic model <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 4P(5-P)</m>, no matter where a solution
    started (above or below <m>M = 5</m>), it converged to <m>M</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>, as long as <m>P(0)>0</m>.
    The equilibrium at <m>P = 5</m> acted like a magnet. The equilibrium at <m>P = 0</m>
    behaved very differently: solutions that started nearby drifted away from it.
    We want language to describe this difference.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       LOGISTIC STATIC GRAPH
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    The figure below shows several solution curves for <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 4P(5-P)</m>
    with different initial values. The equilibrium solutions <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 5</m>
    are highlighted in green. Note that we include a solution with <m>P(0) \lt 0</m>
    as well: while a negative population has no physical meaning, it is still a valid
    solution to the ODE, and it is useful to see how the equation behaves without
    restricting to a population context.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-logistic-trajectories">
    <caption>
      Solution curves for <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 4P(5-P)</m>. The equilibrium solutions
      <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 5</m> are shown in green. All other solutions converge
      to <m>P = 5</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>, regardless of the initial value,
      while solutions near <m>P = 0</m> drift away.
    </caption>
    <interactive xml:id="interactive-logistic-trajectories"
      iframe="ch2-graph/static-logistic-trajectories.html" width="100%" aspect="4:3">
      <static>
        <p>
          Several solution curves for <m>dP/dt = 4P(5-P)</m>. Equilibrium solutions
          <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 5</m> are shown as thick green lines. Curves starting
          above <m>P = 5</m> decrease toward 5. Curves starting between 0 and 5 increase
          toward 5. A curve starting below 0 decreases away from 0. This shows <m>P = 5</m>
          is stable and <m>P = 0</m> is unstable.
        </p>
      </static>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

  <p>
    We say <m>P = 5</m> is <term>stable</term> and <m>P = 0</m> is <term>unstable</term>.
    Here is the precise definition.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       DEFINITION: STABILITY
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <definition xml:id="def-stability">
    <title>Stability of Equilibrium Solutions</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>y(t) = C</m> is an equilibrium solution to a differential equation.
        We say <m>y(t) = C</m> is:
        <ul>
          <li><p>
            <term>stable</term>: if solutions that start near <m>C</m> converge to
            <m>C</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            <term>unstable</term>: if solutions that start near <m>C</m> do not converge
            to <m>C</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            <term>semi-stable</term>: if solutions on one side of <m>C</m> converge to
            <m>C</m>, but solutions on the other side do not.
          </p></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       DOOMSDAY STATIC GRAPH
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    Now compare this with the model from <xref ref="sec-pop-doomsday"/>:
    <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = -2P(10-P)</m>. The equilibrium solutions are still
    <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 10</m>, but the roles are reversed.
    Solutions that start below <m>M = 10</m> decay to zero (extinction),
    and solutions that start above <m>M = 10</m> blow up to infinity in finite time
    (doomsday). Now <m>P = 10</m> is unstable and <m>P = 0</m> is stable.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-doomsday-trajectories">
    <caption>
      Solution curves for <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = -2P(10-P)</m>. The equilibrium solutions
      <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 10</m> are shown in green. Curves starting below
      <m>P = 10</m> decay toward zero. Curves starting above <m>P = 10</m> blow up
      to infinity at a finite doomsday time (marked by vertical dashed lines).
    </caption>
    <interactive xml:id="interactive-doomsday-trajectories"
      iframe="ch2-graph/static-doomsday-trajectories.html" width="100%" aspect="4:3">
      <static>
        <p>
          Several solution curves for <m>dP/dt = -2P(10-P)</m>. Equilibrium solutions
          <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 10</m> are shown as thick green lines. Curves starting
          below <m>P = 10</m> decay to zero (extinction). Curves starting above
          <m>P = 10</m> blow up to infinity at a finite doomsday time, marked by
          vertical red dashed lines. This shows <m>P = 10</m> is unstable and
          <m>P = 0</m> is stable.
        </p>
      </static>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

<p>
  Let's test your understanding of stability in the context of the doomsday/extinction example from above!
</p>
  <exercise xml:id="ex-mc-doomsday-stability">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Based on the second graph above, classify the stability of the equilibrium
      solutions to <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = -2P(10-P)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <choices randomize="no">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>P = 0</m> is stable and <m>P = 10</m> is unstable.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct! Solutions starting near <m>P = 0</m> decay toward it, while solutions
          starting near <m>P = 10</m> move away — either to extinction or doomsday
          depending on which side they start.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>P = 0</m> is unstable and <m>P = 10</m> is stable.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not quite — that describes the logistic case from the first graph.
          Look at what happens to solutions that start near <m>P = 10</m> in the second graph.
          Do they converge to 10 or move away from it?
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p>Both <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 10</m> are stable.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not quite. Look at solutions starting just above <m>P = 10</m> — they blow up
          to infinity rather than returning to 10.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p>Both <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 10</m> are unstable.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not quite. Look at solutions starting near <m>P = 0</m> — they stay close to
          and converge toward zero over time.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       VIDEO NOTE + VIDEO
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

